---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import FindingCard from '@/components/FindingCard.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Clothing Hub — Myprotein Category Landing Page">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">UX Audit: Clothing Category Hub</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Myprotein &mdash; Category Landing Page &mdash; Audited 2 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      This audit covers the Myprotein Clothing hub page at myprotein.com/c/clothing/ — a curated category
      landing page (not a filtered PLP) that funnels users into gendered sub-categories, editorial ranges, and
      product-type tiles. The page structure is sound: clear sub-navigation, strong sale messaging, and
      well-composed lifestyle imagery. However, a modal intercept at entry, a generic non-brand hero CTA,
      contradictory delivery messaging, and absent product-level trust signals represent meaningful conversion
      friction that should be addressed. Design system adherence is mostly good, with two token deviations
      on product cards.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="findings-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Findings</h2>

    <!-- HIGH PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Email capture modal fires immediately on landing"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="entry-modal-intercept"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        A full-screen email capture overlay (Mars Hi-Protein collab, &ldquo;Fuel your ambition — Get 15% off your
        first order&rdquo;) fires as soon as the page loads, blocking the hero banner entirely. The modal contains
        a product image, email field, and CTA. It can be dismissed via an X button or &ldquo;No, thanks&rdquo; link.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Intercepting users at the very first moment of a browse session — before they have expressed any
        intent — is a well-documented conversion anti-pattern. It creates immediate friction, signals
        desperation rather than confidence, and is particularly harmful on a sale period hub page where the
        hero itself (80% off all clothing) is the strongest conversion driver. Users who dismiss and scroll
        back may have already lost their orientation on the page.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Delay the modal trigger to either: (a) exit-intent only, (b) after the user has scrolled 60% of
        the page, or (c) on their second page view in session. Alternatively, consider a less disruptive
        sticky email bar at the bottom of the viewport rather than a full overlay.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Hero CTA uses off-brand button style"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="hero-cta-off-brand"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The primary hero CTA reads &ldquo;SHOP NOW&rdquo; and renders as a plain white rectangle with black uppercase
        text, surrounded by a decorative hand-drawn rust-coloured oval. It is not using the brand button
        design system. Computed styles: <code>background: rgb(255,255,255)</code>, <code>color: rgb(0,0,0)</code>,
        no border-radius value matching the 32px primary CTA spec. This is the most prominent interactive
        element above the fold.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The primary CTA is the single most important conversion element on the hero. An inconsistent
        button style reduces recognisability as a clickable action. Users conditioned to the teal/dark
        primary button elsewhere on the site may not immediately register this as a CTA, especially
        against the dark hero background. The decorative oval obscures rather than emphasises the button.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Replace with the standard primary button: dark teal background (<code>#003942</code> approx),
        white text, Figtree 14px Bold, 32px border-radius, full-width on mobile. Remove the decorative
        oval or repurpose it as a background motif that does not wrap the button directly. Ideally split
        the CTA into &ldquo;Shop Women&rsquo;s&rdquo; and &ldquo;Shop Men&rsquo;s&rdquo; to reduce clicks-to-product.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Contradictory free delivery thresholds shown simultaneously"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="delivery-threshold-conflict"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Two conflicting delivery messages are visible at the same time:
        (1) Trust bar: &ldquo;Free standard delivery on £50 spend&rdquo;
        (2) Under every product card Quick Buy button: &ldquo;FREE DELIVERY ON ALL NEW-IN WHEN YOU SPEND £30 | AUTO APPLIES AT CHECKOUT&rdquo;
        Both messages are visible without scrolling once the product rail loads.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Contradictory threshold messaging is a significant trust-and-conversion issue. A user who has
        added £35 of new-in clothing to their basket may abandon checkout when they see the £50 bar in
        the header and believe they haven&rsquo;t qualified. Confusion around shipping costs is a top-3 reason
        for cart abandonment across ecommerce. The rule needs to be clearly stated in one place, or
        both messages need to reflect the same condition.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Align the two messages. If the £30 new-in threshold is correct, update the trust bar copy.
        If £50 is the correct site-wide figure, remove the £30 card-level message or qualify it clearly
        (&ldquo;on new-in items only&rdquo;). Consider surfacing this as a dynamic spend-to-qualify nudge in the
        basket instead of on product cards.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- MEDIUM PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="&lsquo;Explore New In&rsquo; rail mixes genders without labelling"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="new-in-gender-mixing"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The first product rail (&ldquo;Explore New In&rdquo;) displays women&rsquo;s sports bras and shorts directly
        alongside men&rsquo;s t-shirts and shorts in a single undifferentiated horizontal scroll. No gender
        label, icon, or divider is present to indicate the switch between product types.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A user shopping specifically for women&rsquo;s or men&rsquo;s clothing has to read every product title to
        identify relevance. On a hub page with 4 visible cards, half the rail may be irrelevant to them.
        This is a browse friction issue that increases time-to-relevant-product and may drive premature
        use of the sub-nav instead of engaging with the curated rail.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Either (a) split the rail into separate &ldquo;New In — Women&rsquo;s&rdquo; and &ldquo;New In — Men&rsquo;s&rdquo; sections,
        (b) add a gender filter chip row above the carousel to let users self-select, or (c) sequence
        the products so all women&rsquo;s items come first and add a subtle divider before men&rsquo;s items.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="No star ratings on product cards"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="no-product-card-ratings"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Product cards in the &ldquo;Explore New In&rdquo; rail show image, colour swatches, title, sale price, and
        a Quick Buy button — but no review stars or rating count. The trust bar references &ldquo;Over 210k
        reviews &amp; 4.4 rated&rdquo; (Trustpilot), but this is a site-level claim. No product-level social
        proof is visible at the card level.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Star ratings on product cards are a proven conversion driver on clothing category pages.
        They reduce perceived risk at the moment of first impression, when a shopper is deciding
        whether to click into a PDP. Displaying ratings costs no extra space if placed between the
        title and price, and the site already holds review data for these products.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add a star rating row (average stars + review count) between the product title and the
        price on each card. Suppress the row for products with fewer than 5 reviews to maintain
        credibility. This is standard for Myprotein PDPs — surface it earlier in the funnel.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Product titles include colour variant name"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="title-includes-colour"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Every product title on the card appends the selected colour variant:
        &ldquo;MP Women&rsquo;s Tempo Triangle Sports Bra - Cornflower Blue&rdquo;. The colour is already
        communicated visually by the colour swatch row immediately above the title.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The duplicate colour information makes titles unnecessarily long, causing them to wrap
        to two lines on most cards. This reduces the density of information visible per card
        and makes the product name itself harder to scan. On a hub/browse page, the colour
        is the least important attribute — the product name should be dominant.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Trim the colour suffix from card titles (keep it for PDP breadcrumbs and SEO slugs).
        Display only the core product name: &ldquo;MP Women&rsquo;s Tempo Triangle Sports Bra&rdquo;.
        The swatch row already communicates available colours.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- LOW PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Product card border-radius is 16px (design system specifies 12px)"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="card-border-radius"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Computed border-radius on <code>.product-card</code>: <code>16px</code>.
        The Myprotein design system specifies <code>12px</code> for product cards.
        This is a hardcoded override outside the token scale.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A minor visual inconsistency. At scale, incorrect border-radius values across card types
        create a subtly incoherent feel and make it harder for engineers to rely on a single token
        definition. The deviation is not user-facing enough to affect conversion directly.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Update the <code>.product-card</code> component to use the <code>rounded-card</code> token
        (<code>border-radius: 12px</code>) rather than the hardcoded <code>16px</code> value.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Quick Buy button font size is 16px (spec is 14px)"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="quickbuy-font-size"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Computed styles on <code>.quick-buy.btn.btn-primary</code>: <code>font-size: 16px</code>,
        <code>font-weight: 700</code>, <code>font-family: Figtree</code>.
        The design system specifies <code>14px Bold</code> for button labels.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The font is correct and the button reads clearly at 16px — this is a minor token deviation
        rather than a usability issue. However it means the Quick Buy button is slightly larger
        than other primary buttons on the site, creating minor visual hierarchy inconsistency.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Set <code>font-size: 14px</code> on the <code>.quick-buy</code> component or ensure it
        inherits from the <code>btn-primary</code> token rather than overriding it.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Design Consistency</h2>
    <p>
      Typography: Figtree is loading correctly as the computed font family across all inspected elements
      — no system-font fallback detected. The heading on &ldquo;Explore New In&rdquo; is 28px Bold (close to
      the 32px scale value but off-token). Quick Buy uses Figtree 700 at 16px (spec: 14px).
      The primary navigation and sub-navigation are consistent in size and weight.
    </p>
    <p>
      Buttons: Quick Buy button border-radius is correctly 32px. Background colour is a dark teal
      (<code>oklch(0.3162 0.055061 211.831)</code> — approximately <code>#003942</code>), consistent with
      the primary button definition. The hero &ldquo;SHOP NOW&rdquo; button is the sole design system deviation
      on buttons: white background, black text, no radius — clearly a custom campaign style rather than
      a design system component.
    </p>
    <p>
      Cards: Product card border-radius is 16px (should be 12px per token spec). Card background is a
      warm off-white (<code>oklch(0.9654 0.006 75.41)</code>) consistent across all cards — this appears
      intentional and on-brand. No mint (<code>#94E5B5</code>) ring observed on any element other than
      the expected Add to Basket context — correct.
    </p>
    <p>
      Spacing: Padding and margin values on inspected elements appear to follow the 4px grid. No
      obviously out-of-scale values detected.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Accessibility Notes</h2>
    <p>
      Colour contrast on primary CTA (Quick Buy): white text on dark teal background — passes WCAG AA
      comfortably (estimated ratio &gt;7:1). Hero banner text (orange and white on black) — both pass
      large-text AA thresholds.
    </p>
    <p>
      The hero &ldquo;SHOP NOW&rdquo; CTA is a concern: black text on white background passes contrast, but the
      surrounding decorative oval could be misread as the button boundary by users relying on visual
      affordance cues, and may confuse screen reader context if the oval is not marked decorative.
    </p>
    <p>
      The email modal has a visible close button (X) and a &ldquo;No, thanks&rdquo; dismiss link. Both appear
      keyboard-accessible. However, showing a modal on page load is a WCAG 2.1 AA risk for users
      with cognitive disabilities — screen readers will jump focus into the dialog immediately,
      disorienting users who landed on the clothing hub with a specific browsing intent.
    </p>
    <p>
      Product images appear to show model shots — alt text should describe the garment, not just the
      model pose. This could not be fully verified from the live page without deeper inspection.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Conversion Summary</h2>
    <p>
      This is a hub/category landing page rather than a filter-and-browse PLP — its job is to funnel
      users into the right sub-category or product rail efficiently. The structure does this reasonably
      well: the sub-navigation (Trending / Women&rsquo;s / Men&rsquo;s / Accessories / Footwear / Sale / Shop by
      Training Type) is clear, and the mid-page gender tiles (Men&rsquo;s / Women&rsquo;s / Accessories with Shop Now)
      provide a strong visual fallback for users who scroll past the sub-nav. The sale messaging
      (Impact Week, up to 80% off) is prominent and credible.
    </p>
    <p>
      The three highest-impact conversion blockers are the modal intercept (interrupts intent before
      browsing begins), the delivery threshold conflict (plants doubt at the moment of commitment),
      and the absence of product ratings (removes social proof at first product impression). Fixing
      these three in sequence is likely to produce measurable uplift on click-through from the hub
      to PDPs and on add-to-basket rate for Quick Buy items.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Recommended Implementation Order</h2>
    <ol class="recommendations">
      <li>Resolve the delivery threshold conflict (£30 new-in vs £50 site-wide) — copy change, no design work needed, immediate trust uplift.</li>
      <li>Delay the email capture modal — trigger on exit-intent or scroll-depth rather than page load. Engineering change, low risk.</li>
      <li>Add star ratings to product cards — surface existing review data at card level between title and price.</li>
      <li>Split the hero CTA into &ldquo;Shop Women&rsquo;s&rdquo; / &ldquo;Shop Men&rsquo;s&rdquo; and apply brand button styles — requires design spec and engineering implementation.</li>
      <li>Remove colour suffix from product card titles — CMS/template change, reduces title wrapping and improves scannability.</li>
      <li>Gender-label or split the &ldquo;Explore New In&rdquo; rail — design decision required before engineering acts.</li>
      <li>Fix product card border-radius token (16px → 12px) — low effort, design system hygiene.</li>
      <li>Fix Quick Buy font-size (16px → 14px) — minor CSS token correction.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style is:global>
  .finding-card code {
    font-family: Menlo, Monaco, 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    padding: 1px 5px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
  }
</style>

<style>
  .report-intro { margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .report-h1 { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text-heading); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .report-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.65; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .report-summary { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); max-width: 680px; }
  .findings-section { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .section-heading { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 20px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .prose-section { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  .prose-section p { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); margin-bottom: 12px; }
  .recommendations { padding-left: 20px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; }
  .recommendations li { font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--color-text-body); }
</style>
